{
  "text": "Comparison of the timing of enhanced ice-rafted debris (IRD) deposition and low surface water temperatures [CITATION_1] in the North Atlantic (peaks at about 1.4, 2.8, 4.2, 5.9, 8.1, 9.4, 10.3 and 11.1 ka BP) with changes in the oxygen isotope composition of diatoms from Lake Kotokel sediments also suggests that the IRD events in the North Atlantic might show a response in the Lake Kotokel isotopic record. All these dates are marked by visible changes in the isotopic composition of diatoms: the events of 10.3, 8.1, 5.9, 2.8, 1.4 The synchronicity of climate events in the Kotokel isotope record and the sequence of North Atlantic cooling events suggest that the large-scale climatic shifts in the North Atlantic region might have influenced the Lake Kotokel diatom isotope composition. The character of the isotope record obtained for Lake Kotokel is similar to that obtained for Swedish Lapland (Lake 850: [CITATION_2] Vuolep Allakasjaure: Rosqvist et al., 2004) . All curves show a general depletion trend in d",
